":"1283","1282":"1282","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Jórvík, England","Corkeby,  England":"England","England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1210–1308":"1210–1308","1203–1242":"1203–1242","1228–1283":"1228–1283","–1282":"–1282","1180–Female":"1180–Overleden","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1242":"1242","1283":"1283","1282":"1282","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Corkeby,  England":"England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1210–1308":"1210–1308","1203–1242":"1203–1242","1228–1283":"1228–1283","–1282":"–1282","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1242":"1242","1283":"1283","1282":"1282","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Corkeby,  England":"England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lasceles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one of the large number of places in northern France called Celle, Celles, Lacelle, Leschelle, or Lachelle, all from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’, and at different times occurring both with and without the plural <i>-s</i>.","Variant of   Lacelle   1, a surname of French origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Laswell","meanings":["English: possibly an altered form of   Lascelles  . This surname is also found as   Lacefield  ."]},{"name":"Lasell","meanings":["English: variant of   Lascelles  ."]},{"name":"Lacelle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Andre, Aurele, Benoit, Cecile, Marcel, Marie Paule.","Altered form of French <b>Laselle</b>: habitational name from La Selle, the name of several places in various parts of France. The surname <i>Laselle</i> is very rare in France, found in Marne. Compare   Lascelles  .","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Lacelle in Corrèze or numerous minor places called La Celle, all named for a monastic cell or hermitage in their vicinity, from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":80,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Lasceles was born in 1210, in York, Yorkshire, England as the son of Alan Lasceles and Osanna de Langthwayt. He had at least 1 daughter with Ossana Langthwayte. He died in 1308, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 98."},"et":{"1210–1308":"1210–1308","1203–1242":"1203–1242","1228–1283":"1228–1283","–1282":"–1282","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1242":"1242","1283":"1283","1282":"1282","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Corkeby,  England":"England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1210–1308":"1210–1308","1203–1242":"1203–1242","1228–1283":"1228–1283","–1282":"–1282","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1242":"1242","1283":"1283","1282":"1282","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Corkeby,  England":"England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1210–1308":"1210–1308","1203–1242":"1203–1242","1228–1283":"1228–1283","–1282":"–1282","1180–Female":"1180–Décédée","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1242":"